# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adam-kendon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon was born on 4 April 1934 in London, son of the writer Frank Kendon and Elizabeth Cecilia Phyllis Horne, a school teacher.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] At the University of Cambridge, he read Botany, Zoology and Human Physiology, as well as Experimental Psychology for the Natural Sciences.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] At the University of Oxford, he studied Experimental Psychology, focusing on the temporal organization of utterances in conversation, using Eliot Chapple's chronography.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Then he moved to Cornell University to study directly with Chapple on research leading to his D.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] His thesis topic—communication conduct in face-to-face interaction—spelled out the interests he would pursue in subsequent decades.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] He is noted for his study of gesture and sign languages and how these relate to spoken language.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Phil., he accepted a position in the Institute of Experimental Psychology at Oxford, where he worked in a research group with Michael Argyle and E.R.W.F.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] He initially focused on sign systems in Papua New Guinea and Australian Aboriginal sign languages, before developing a general framework for understanding gestures with the same kind of rigorous semiotic analysis as has been previously applied to spoken language.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Important influences on his theoretical understandings included: Erving Goffman, Albert Scheflen, Ray Birdwhistell, and Gregory Bateson.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Becoming aware of Scheflen's work in 1965, while still at Oxford, he managed to meet him in Philadelphia, where he shared his earliest work; as a result, he was first invited to join William S.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Condon's research team at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic in 1966-67, and then to join Scheflen's research team at Bronx State Hospital in 1967.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] He never actually worked with Birdwhistell directly, but they were in contact, and he did work with films made available to him by Birdwhistell.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] In 1976 he took up an appointment in Canberra, Australia at the Department of Anthropology in the Research School of Pacific Studies, Australian National University.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] He undertook filming everyday interaction in Papua New Guinea but also was able to record a sign language in use in the valley where he worked where there was a considerable number of deaf persons.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] His publication of this work, in three articles in 1980, proved to be a pioneering study; no other accounts on sign language from this part of the world were to appear until the beginning of the twenty-first century.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] This work was republished as a monograph together with a new essay written by colleagues bringing the original work up to date.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] After this he undertook a major investigation of the sign languages in use among indigenous Australians - these are sign languages used for ritual reasons or for practical reasons in situations where speech might is impractical or inappropriate.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] These are known as alternate sign languages, distinguishing them from primary sign languages developed among deaf people.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Extensive documentation of his research in Australia is available at the library of the Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] In 1988, he returned to Philadelphia, teaching for two years at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon then moved to Naples, Italy and undertook fieldwork on the use of gesture in everyday interaction among Neapolitans and also published a translation of a 19th Century book about Neapolitan gesture (by Andrea de Jorio), comparing it to gesturing among the Greeks and Romans.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] In 2004 he published an important general book on the phenomena of gesture which drew extensively on his work in Naples as well as his work in New Guinea and Australia, the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Since then he has published various articles on gesture and related topics, including discussions of the place of gesture in theories about language origins.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] In 2012, he returned to Cambridge, where he spent the rest of his life, associated with the Division of Biological Anthropology at Cambridge, and an Honorary Professor in Psychology and Language Sciences at University College London.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon received research grants from the National Science Foundation, the Wenner-Gren Foundation for Anthropological Research, the American Council of Learned Societies, as well as a Guggenheim Fellowship.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] In addition to teaching at Oxford and Penn, he held positions at Cornell University and Connecticut College in the US, as well as the Università degli Studi di Napoli "L'Orientale", the University of Salerno and the University of Calabria in Italy.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon was a founding editor of the journal *GESTURE* (published by John Benjamins of Amsterdam), along with Cornelia Müller, in 2000.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] He was the sole editor from 2010 to April 2017, when he was replaced by Sotaro Kita.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] In his role as editor of *GESTURE* he was an Ex Officio member of the board of the International Society for Gesture Studies, of which he was elected Honorary President in 2006.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] He edited the book series *Gesture Studies* for John Benjamins, with 9 volumes published between 2007 and 2022.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Colleagues prepared a festschrift in 2014, honoring his contribution to the study of gestures and interaction.
[src:adam-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon married Margaret Rhoads in 1961; they had three children, Gudrun, Benjamin and Angus.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The **American Council of Learned Societies** (**ACLS**) is a private, nonprofit federation of 75 scholarly organizations in the humanities and related social sciences founded in 1919.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The federation was created in 1919 to represent the United States in the Union Académique Internationale (International Union of Academies).
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The founders of ACLS, representatives of 13 learned societies, believed that a federation of scholarly organizations (dedicated to excellence in research, and most with open membership) was the best combination of U.S. democracy and intellectual aspirations.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] According to the council's constitution, its mission was advancing humanistic studies and social sciences and maintaining and strengthening national societies dedicated to those studies.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Since its founding, ACLS has provided the humanities and related social sciences with leadership, opportunities for innovation, and national and international representation.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The council's many activities have at their core the practice of scholarly self-governance.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Central to ACLS throughout its history have been its programs of fellowships and grants aiding research.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] ACLS made its first grants, totaling $4,500, in 1926; in 2012, ACLS awarded over $15 million in fellowship stipends and other awards to more than 320 scholars in the United States and abroad.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] All ACLS awards are made through rigorous peer review by specially appointed committees of scholars from throughout the United States and, in some programs, abroad.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] During the late 1950s, the council encouraged Hans Wehr in his writing of the first English edition of his *Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic* (1962).
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The executive directors of the ACLS member societies meet in a Conference of Administrative Officers (CAO); before 1988, this was the Conference of Secretaries.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] At its first meeting in 1925 the conference had 11 members, including Frederic Ogg of the American Political Science Association and Ernest Burgess of the American Sociological Society (now the American Sociological Association).
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In addition to peer review, the ACLS has organized committees to research promising fields of study.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The concept of organizing expertise around a cultural region grew out of the council's early work in Far Eastern and Slavic studies.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] After World War II, when the practical need for such competence was evident, the ACLS and the Social Science Research Council developed African, Asian, Latin American, Near and Middle Eastern, Slavic, and East and West European studies.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1927 the ACLS Committee on Research in Native American Languages, under the leadership of Franz Boas and Edward Sapir, began in 1927 to "secure an adequate record of Indian languages and dialects." The Committee on a Journal of Medieval Studies, begun in 1924, founded the journal *Speculum*.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The Committee on the History of Ideas, which included Richard McKeon and Arthur Oncken Lovejoy, created the *Journal of the History of Ideas*.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Since the introduction of new research technology, the ACLS has helped scholars explore the impact of new technologies on their fields.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1964 the council developed a grant and fellowship program to encourage computer use in humanistic research, which continues in its Digital Innovation Fellowships.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] *Our Cultural Commonwealth*, the 2006 report by the ACLS Commission on Cyberinfrastructure for the Humanities and Social Sciences, recommended digital humanities using new forms of research, reading and writing.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS has an interest in the problems of scholarly publication and has conducted a survey of publication needs, established a publication service to advise scholars on communicating research and aided scholars with subsidies and publication.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS-sponsored National Enquiry into the Production and Dissemination of Scholarly Knowledge investigated all aspects of the dissemination of humanistic scholarship from 1974 to 1979.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1979 it presented a report, *Scholarly Communication: The Report of the National Enquiry*, published by the Johns Hopkins University Press and operated its Office of Scholarly Communication and Technology in Washington, D.C. until 1984.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Today, the ACLS Humanities E-Book collection focuses on how digital innovations can enhance scholarly communication.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] By bringing scholars together as scholars rather than as specialists, the ACLS advocates for the humanities in public forums and policy arenas.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The council's role in establishing (in 1964) and reauthorizing (in 1985) the National Endowment for the Humanities is an example.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] While continuing to represent the U.S. in the *Union Académique Internationale*, the ACLS has participated in international scholarly exchange.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] From 1961 to 1992, its American Studies Program aided overseas scholars specializing in the study of the U.S.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The council and other members of the Associated Board of Research Councils founded the Council for International Exchange of Scholars, which administers the graduating-senior Fulbright Program.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1992 the United States Information Agency asked the ACLS to reinstitute the Fulbright Program in Vietnam, operated by the U.S.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS Center for Educational Exchange with Vietnam offers fellowship and study opportunities to Vietnamese scholars.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1966 the ACLS, the Social Science Research Council and the National Academy of Sciences founded the Committee on Scholarly Communication with China, which maintains an office in Beijing to assist American schools with programs in that country.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS has extended its support of research to scholars in the former USSR through the ACLS Humanities Program in Belarus, Russia and Ukraine, and in Africa through its African Humanities Program.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In June 1999 under its President John D'Arms, ACLS received a $3-million, 5-year grant from The Andrew W.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Mellon Foundation to initiate The History E-Book Project.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In October 1999, Eileen Gardiner and Ronald G.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Musto of Italica Press became the project directors working in collaboration with the Scholarly Publishing Office of the University of Michigan Library and with New York University Press.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Three years later and two years ahead of schedule, on September 1, 2002, the History E-Book Project website launched online with over 500 titles.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] These had been reviewed and recommended by historians and scholarly societies and were often award-winning books in different area specialties.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] "HEB continued to grow and to adjust accordingly, becoming self-sufficient in 2005, garnering attention and a supportive constituency among scholars, presses, libraries, and learned societies." HEB mission expanded to include all the humanities disciplines and was renamed ACLS Humanities E-Book.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] At the end of 2019, ACLS transferred the management and administration of Humanities E-Book to the University of Michigan, where this online collection of over 5,400 books of high quality in the humanities and related social sciences is accessible through institutional subscription.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS' organizational structure has experienced few major changes during the council's existence.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Most notable is the growth in the number of member societies, from 13 to 71.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] As the number of societies increased, it became impossible for a council with two representatives of each member to govern effectively.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1947 a council-elected board of directors was created, and the number of delegates from each society was reduced to one.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Another change occurred in 1957; the council moved its headquarters from Washington to New York and appointed Frederick Burkhardt its first president, signaling a new determination to place scholarship at the center of public culture.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS was incorporated in the District of Columbia in 1924, receiving a congressional charter in 1982.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] For the fiscal year ending June 30, 2017, the ACLS reported an endowment of US$120 million.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] During the same period the institution distributed about US$15.9 million in grants and fellowships.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS archives are in the Manuscript Division of the Library of Congress.
[src:adam-kendon/american-council-of-learned-societies] Graves Awards in the Humanities or Arnold L.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was founded at the mouth of the Amstel river, which was dammed to control flooding.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Originally a small fishing village in the 12th century, Amsterdam became a major world port during the Dutch Golden Age of the 17th century, when the Netherlands was an economic powerhouse.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was the leading centre for finance and trade, as well as a hub of secular art production.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the 19th and 20th centuries, the city expanded and new neighborhoods and suburbs were built.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city has a long tradition of openness, liberalism, and tolerance.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Cycling is key to the city's modern character, and there are numerous biking paths and lanes spread throughout.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city is known for its nightlife and festival activity, with several nightclubs among the world's most famous.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Its artistic heritage, canals, and narrow canal houses with gabled façades, well-preserved legacies of the city's 17th-century Golden Age, have attracted millions of visitors annually.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange, founded in 1602, is considered the oldest "modern" securities market stock exchange in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] As the commercial capital of the Netherlands and one of the top financial centres in Europe, Amsterdam is considered an alpha-world city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city is the cultural capital of the Netherlands.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Many large Dutch institutions have their headquarters in the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Many of the world's largest companies are based in Amsterdam or have established their European headquarters there, such as technology companies Uber, Netflix, and Tesla.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Although Amsterdam is the official capital of the Netherlands, it is not the seat of government.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The main governmental institutions, and foreign embassies, are located in The Hague.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 2022, Amsterdam was ranked the ninth-best city to live in by the Economist Intelligence Unit and 12th on quality of living for environment and infrastructure by Mercer.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city was ranked 4th place globally as a top tech hub in 2019.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Port of Amsterdam is the fifth largest in Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The KLM hub and Amsterdam's main airport, Schiphol, is the busiest airport in the Netherlands, and third in Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Dutch capital is one of the most multicultural cities in the world, with about 180 nationalities represented.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Immigration and ethnic segregation in Amsterdam is a current issue.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's notable residents throughout its history include painters Rembrandt and Vincent van Gogh, 17th-century philosophers Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, René Descartes, and John Amos Comenius, and Holocaust victim and diarist Anne Frank.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Due to its geographical location in what used to be wet peatland, the founding of Amsterdam is later than other urban centres in the Low Countries.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] However, around the area of what later became Amsterdam, farmers settled as early as three millennia ago.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] They lived along the prehistoric IJ river and upstream of its tributary Amstel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The prehistoric IJ was a shallow and quiet stream in peatland behind beach ridges.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This secluded area was able to grow into an important local settlement centre, especially in the late Bronze Age, the Iron Age and the Roman Age.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Until water issues were controlled, a permanent settlement would not have been possible, since the river mouth and the banks of the Amstel in this period in time were too wet for permanent habitation.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The origins of Amsterdam are linked to the development of a dam on the Amstel River called *Amestelle*, meaning 'watery area', from *Aa(m)* 'river' + *stelle* 'site at a shoreline', 'river bank'.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In this area, land reclamation started as early as the late 10th century.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amestelle was located along a side arm of the IJ.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This sidearm took its name from the eponymous land: Amstel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amestelle was inhabited by farmers, who lived more inland and more upstream, where the land was not as wet as at the banks of the downstream river mouth.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] These farmers were starting the reclamation around upstream Ouderkerk aan de Amstel, and later at the other side of the river at Amstelveen.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Van Amstel family, known in documents by this name since 1019, held the stewardship in this northwestern nook of the ecclesiastical district of the bishop of Utrecht.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The family later served also under the count of Holland.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A major turning point in the development of the Amstel River mouth was the All Saint's Flood of 1170.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In an extremely short time, the shallow river IJ turned into a wide estuary, which from then on offered the Amstel an open connection to the Zuiderzee, IJssel, and waterways further afield.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This made the water flow of the Amstel more active, so excess water could be drained better.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] With drier banks, the downstream Amstel mouth became attractive for permanent habitation.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Moreover, the river had grown from an insignificant peat stream into a junction of international waterways.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A settlement was built here immediately after the landscape change of 1170.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Right from the start of its foundation it focused on traffic, production, and trade; not on farming, as opposed to how communities had lived further upstream for the past 200 years and northward for thousands of years.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The construction of a dam at the mouth of the Amstel, eponymously named Dam, is historically estimated to have occurred between 1264 and 1275.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The settlement first appeared in a document from 1275, concerning a road toll granted by the count of Holland Floris V to the residents *apud Amestelledamme* 'at the dam in the Amstel' or 'at the dam of Amstelland'.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This allowed the inhabitants of the village to travel freely through the County of Holland, paying no tolls at bridges, locks and dams.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This was a move in a years-long struggle for power in the area between the count of Holland and the Amstel family who governed the area on behalf of the bishop of Utrecht.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] By 1327, the name had developed into *Aemsterdam*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The bishop of Utrecht granted Amsterdam zone rights in either 1300 or 1306.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Mirakel van Amsterdam in 1345 rendered the city an important place of pilgrimage.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] During the heyday of the *Stille Omgang*, which became the expression of the pilgrimage after the Protestant Reformation, up to 90,000 pilgrims came to Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] From the 14th century on, Amsterdam flourished, largely from trade with the Hanseatic League.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] From the 15th century on the city established an independent trade route with the Baltic Sea in grain and timber, cutting out the Hanseatic League as middlemen.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city became the staple market of Europe for bulk cargo.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This was made possible due to innovations in the herring fishery, from which Amsterdam reaped great wealth.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Herring had demand in markets all around Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Inventions of on-board gibbing and the haringbuis in 1415, made longer voyages feasible and hence enabled Dutch fishermen to follow the herring shoals far from the coasts, giving them a monopoly in the industry.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The herring industry relied on international trade cooperation and large initial investments in ships.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This required many highly skilled and unskilled workers to cooperate, as well as the import of the necessary raw materials to turn an unfinished product into a marketable one.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This required merchants to then sell it throughout the continent and bookkeepers and accountants to divide the profit.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In short, the herring industry was setting up the foundations for what would later become the transcontinental trade system and the Dutch Golden Age, with Amsterdam at its centre, hence the saying "Amsterdam is built on Herringbones".
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Low Countries were part of the Habsburg inheritance and came under the Spanish Empire in the early sixteenth century.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Dutch rebelled against Philip II of Spain, who led a defense of Catholicism during the Protestant Reformation.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The main reasons for the uprising were the imposition of new taxes, the tenth penny, and the religious persecution of Protestants by the newly introduced Inquisition.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The revolt escalated into the Eighty Years' War, which ultimately led to Dutch independence.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Strongly pushed by Dutch Revolt leader William the Silent, the Dutch Republic became known for its relative religious tolerance.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Jews from the Iberian Peninsula, Protestant Huguenots from France, prosperous merchants, and printers from Flanders, and economic and religious refugees from the Spanish-controlled parts of the Low Countries found safety in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The influx of Flemish printers and the city's intellectual tolerance made Amsterdam a centre for the European free press.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] During the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced what is considered its *Golden Age*, during which it became the wealthiest city in the Western world.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Ships sailed from Amsterdam to the Baltic Sea, the Caribbean, North America, and Africa, as well as present-day Indonesia, India, Sri Lanka, and Brazil, forming the basis of a worldwide trading network.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's merchants had the largest share in both the Dutch East India Company (VOC) and the Dutch West India Company.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] These companies acquired overseas possessions that later became Dutch colonies.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam was Europe's most important hub for the shipment of goods and was the leading financial centre of the Western world.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1602, the Amsterdam office of the Dutch East India Company became the world's first stock exchange by trading in its own shares.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Bank of Amsterdam started operations in 1609, acting as a full-service bank for Dutch merchant bankers and as a reserve bank.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] From the 17th century onwards, Amsterdam also became involved in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city was a major destination port for Dutch slave ships participating in the triangular trade, which lasted until the United Netherlands abolished the Netherlands' involvement in the trade in 1814 at the request of the British government.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's prosperity declined during the 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The wars of the Dutch Republic with England (latterly, Great Britain) and France took their toll on the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars and the Napoleonic Wars, Amsterdam's significance reached its lowest point, with Holland being absorbed into the French Empire.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] However, the later establishment of the United Kingdom of the Netherlands in 1815 marked a turning point.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The end of the 19th century is sometimes called Amsterdam's second Golden Age.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] New museums, a railway station, and the Concertgebouw were built; At the same time, the Industrial Revolution reached the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam–Rhine Canal was dug to give Amsterdam a direct connection to the Rhine, and the North Sea Canal was dug to give the port a shorter connection to the North Sea.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Both projects dramatically improved commerce with the rest of Europe and the world.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1906, Joseph Conrad gave a brief description of Amsterdam as seen from the seaside, in *The Mirror of the Sea*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Shortly before the First World War, the city started to expand again, and new suburbs were built.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Even though the Netherlands remained neutral in this war, Amsterdam suffered a food shortage, and heating fuel became scarce.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The shortages sparked riots in which several people were killed.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] These riots are known as the *Aardappeloproer* (Potato Rebellion).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] People started looting stores and warehouses to get supplies, mainly food.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] On 1 January 1921, after a flood in 1916, the depleted municipalities of Durgerdam, Holysloot, Zunderdorp and Schellingwoude (all lying north of Amsterdam) were, at their own request, annexed to the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Between the wars, the city continued to expand, most notably to the west of the Jordaan district in the Frederik Hendrikbuurt and surrounding neighbourhoods.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Nazi Germany invaded the Netherlands on 10 May 1940 and took control of the country.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Some Amsterdam citizens sheltered Jews, thereby exposing themselves and their families to a high risk of being imprisoned or sent to concentration camps.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] More than 100,000 Dutch Jews were deported and murdered in Nazi concentration camps, including 56,521 victims in Auschwitz and a further number of 34,082 accounted for in Sobibor.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Around 60,000 Jewish inhabitants, including Jewish prewar refugees from Austria and Germany, were living in Amsterdam at the time of the Nazi occupation.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Only those provided with a safe haven, avoiding deportation and denunciation, or the very few who returned from the camps at the end of the war, managed to survive.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] At first the German occupation authorities were very cautious, wanting to convince the city inhabitants of their sincerity.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] However, their outlook soon turned to cynicism and brutality.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A cause in the change of their behaviour was an attack by a Dutch resistance fighter against a collaborator belonging to the paramilitary Dutch fascist organisation, the NSB.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The injured man died and in response Heinrich Himmler ordered reprisals.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] 427 Amsterdam Jews were arrested on 22 February 1941 and sent to Mauthausen concentration camp.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Incensed, a broad spectrum of passive resistance was organized by the Dutch Underground.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Trade unions, among them socialist and Communist Party activists, led the protest.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Their outcry received support from white collar employees in the civil service and support from the local diocese of the Church.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Approval was also given and encouraged by the Dutch government-in-exile under Queen Wilhelmina in London.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The German authorities were taken completely by surprise by the level of resistance known as the February strike.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] 300,000 people participated in the protest against the arrests of Jews.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] However, the occupier soon responded crudely and brutally, smashing union and illegal party activity.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] With the edifice of resistance removed the SS and German police apparatus, supported by collaborators in the Dutch auxiliary police, arrested thousands of defenceless Jews in Amsterdam's Jewish Quarter.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The two main waves of arrest, culminating in deportation, occurred on 26 May 1943 and on 20 June 1943.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The most famous deportee was the young Jewish girl Anne Frank, whose safe hiding place with her family was betrayed and discovered in August, 1944.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] After a spell at the 'holding camp' in Westerbork Anna and her family were sent to Auschwitz, where her mother was murdered.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] From there she and her sister Margot were moved onto Bergen-Belsen concentration camp where they died amidst appalling and inhumane conditions in early 1945.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] At the end of the Second World War, and as a consequence of the Nazi occupation, Amsterdam was in a state of crisis.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Communication with the rest of the country broke down, and food and fuel became scarce.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Many citizens traveled to the countryside to forage.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Dogs, cats, raw sugar beets, and tulip bulbs—cooked to a pulp—were consumed to stay alive.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Many trees in Amsterdam were cut down for fuel, and wood was taken from the houses, apartments and other buildings of deported Jews.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city was finally liberated by Canadian forces on 5 May 1945, shortly before the end of the war in Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Many new suburbs, such as Osdorp, Slotervaart, Slotermeer and Geuzenveld, were built in the years after the Second World War.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] These suburbs contained many public parks and wide-open spaces, and the new buildings provided improved housing conditions with larger and brighter rooms, gardens, and balconies.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Because of the war and other events of the 20th century, almost the entire city centre had fallen into disrepair.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] As society was changing, politicians and other influential figures made plans to redesign large parts of it.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] There was an increasing demand for office buildings, and also for new roads, as the automobile became available to most people.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A metro started operating in 1977 between the new suburb of Bijlmermeer in the city's Zuidoost (southeast) exclave and the centre of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Further plans were to build a new highway above the metro to connect Amsterdam Centraal and the city centre with other parts of the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The required large-scale demolitions began in Amsterdam's former Jewish neighborhood.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Smaller streets, such as the Jodenbreestraat and Weesperstraat, were widened and almost all houses and buildings were demolished.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] At the peak of the demolition, the *Nieuwmarktrellen* (Nieuwmarkt riots) broke out; the rioters expressed their fury about the demolition caused by the restructuring of the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] As a result, the demolition was stopped and the highway into the city's centre was never fully built; only the metro was completed.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The new city hall was built on the almost completely demolished Waterlooplein.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Meanwhile, large private organizations, such as *Stadsherstel Amsterdam*, were founded to restore the entire city centre.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Although the success of this struggle is visible today, efforts for further restoration are still ongoing.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The entire city centre has reattained its former splendour and, as a whole, is now a protected area.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Many of its buildings have become monuments, and in July 2010 the Grachtengordel (the three concentric canals: Herengracht, Keizersgracht, and Prinsengracht) was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the 21st century, the Amsterdam city centre has attracted large numbers of tourists: between 2012 and 2015, the annual number of visitors rose from 10 to 17 million.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Real estate prices have surged, and local shops are making way for tourist-oriented ones, making the centre unaffordable for the city's inhabitants.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] These developments have evoked comparisons with Venice, a city thought to be overwhelmed by the tourist influx.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Construction of a new metro line connecting the part of the city north of the IJ to its southern part was started in 2003.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The project was controversial because its cost had exceeded its budget by a factor of three by 2008, because of fears of damage to buildings in the centre, and because construction had to be halted and restarted multiple times.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The new metro line was completed in 2018.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Since 2014, renewed focus has been given to urban regeneration and renewal, especially in areas directly bordering the city centre, such as Frederik Hendrikbuurt.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This urban renewal and expansion of the traditional centre of the city—with the construction of artificial islands of the new eastern IJburg neighbourhood—is part of the Structural Vision Amsterdam 2040 initiative.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is located in the Western Netherlands, in the province of North Holland, the capital of which is not Amsterdam, but rather Haarlem.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The river Amstel ends in the city centre and connects to a large number of canals that eventually terminate in the IJ.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's elevation is about −2 m (−6.6 ft) below sea level.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The surrounding land is flat as it is formed of large polders.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] An artificial forest, Amsterdamse Bos, is in the southwest.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is connected to the North Sea by the North Sea Canal.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam is intensely urbanised, as is the Metropolitan Region Amsterdam surrounding the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Comprising 219.4 km2 (84.7 sq mi) of land, the city proper has 4,457 inhabitants per km2 and 2,275 houses per km2.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Parks and nature reserves make up 12% of Amsterdam's land area.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has more than 100 km (60 mi) of canals, most of which are navigable by boat.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city's three main canals are the Prinsengracht, the Herengracht, and the Keizersgracht.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the Middle Ages, Amsterdam was surrounded by a moat, called the Singel, which now forms the innermost ring in the city, and gives the city centre a horseshoe shape.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] It has been compared with Venice, due to its division into about 90 islands, which are linked by more than 1,200 bridges.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*) strongly influenced by its proximity to the North Sea to the west, with prevailing westerly winds.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam, as well as most of the North Holland province, lies in USDA Hardiness zone 8b.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Frosts mainly occur during spells of easterly or northeasterly winds from the inner European continent.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Even then, because Amsterdam is surrounded on three sides by large bodies of water, as well as having a significant heat-island effect, nights rarely fall below −5 °C (23 °F), while it could easily be −12 °C (10 °F) in Hilversum, 25 km (16 mi) southeast.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Summers are moderately warm with several hot and humid days with occasional rain every month.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The average daily high in August is 22.1 °C (72 °F), and 30 °C (86 °F) or higher is only measured on average on 2.5 days, placing Amsterdam in AHS Heat Zone 2.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Days with more than 1 mm (0.04 in) of precipitation are common, on average 133 days per year.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's average annual precipitation is 838 mm (33 in).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A large part of this precipitation falls as light rain or brief showers.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Cloudy and damp days are common during the cooler months of October through March.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1300, Amsterdam's population was around 1,000 people.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] While many towns in Holland experienced population decline during the 15th and 16th centuries, Amsterdam's population grew, mainly due to the rise of the profitable Baltic maritime trade especially in grain after the Burgundian victory in the Dutch–Hanseatic War in 1441.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The population of Amsterdam was only modest compared to the towns and cities of Flanders and Brabant, which comprised the most urbanized area of the Low Countries.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This changed when, during the Dutch Revolt, many people from the Southern Netherlands fled to the North, especially after Antwerp fell to Spanish forces in 1585.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Jews from Spain, Portugal, and Eastern Europe similarly settled in Amsterdam, as did Germans and Scandinavians.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In thirty years, Amsterdam's population more than doubled between 1585 and 1610.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] During the 1660s, Amsterdam's population reached 200,000.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city's growth levelled off and the population stabilized around 240,000 for most of the 18th century.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1750, Amsterdam was the fourth largest city in Western Europe, behind London (676,000), Paris (560,000) and Naples (324,000).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This was all the more remarkable as Amsterdam was neither the capital city nor the seat of government of the Dutch Republic, which itself was a much smaller state than Great Britain, France or the Ottoman Empire.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In contrast to those other metropolises, Amsterdam was also surrounded by large towns such as Leiden (about 67,000), Rotterdam (45,000), Haarlem (38,000), and Utrecht (30,000).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city's population declined in the early 19th century, dipping under 200,000 in 1820.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] By the second half of the 19th century, industrialization spurred renewed growth.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam's population hit an all-time high of 872,000 in 1959, before declining in the following decades due to government-sponsored suburbanisation to so-called *groeikernen* (growth centres) such as Purmerend and Almere.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Between 1970 and 1980, Amsterdam experienced a sharp population decline, peaking at a net loss of 25,000 people in 1973.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] By 1985 the city had only 675,570 residents.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This was soon followed by reurbanization and gentrification, leading to renewed population growth in the 2010s.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Also in the 2010s, much of Amsterdam's population growth was due to immigration to the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the 16th and 17th centuries, non-Dutch immigrants to Amsterdam were mostly Protestant Huguenots and Flemings, Sephardic Jews, and Westphalians.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Huguenots came after the Edict of Fontainebleau in 1685, while the Flemish Protestants came during the Eighty Years' War against Catholic Spain.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Westphalians came to Amsterdam mostly for economic reasons; their influx continued through the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Before the Second World War, 10% of the city population was Jewish.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Just twenty percent of them survived the Holocaust.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam experienced an influx of religions and cultures after the Second World War.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] With 180 different nationalities, Amsterdam is home to one of the widest varieties of nationalities of any city in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The proportion of the population of immigrant origin in the city proper is about 50% and 88% of the population are Dutch citizens.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The first mass immigration in the 20th century was by people from Indonesia, who came to Amsterdam after the independence of the Dutch East Indies in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the 1960s guest workers from Turkey, Morocco, Italy, and Spain immigrated to Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] After the independence of Suriname in 1975, a large wave of Surinamese settled in Amsterdam, mostly in the Bijlmer area.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Other immigrants, including refugees asylum seekers and undocumented immigrants, came from Europe, the Americas, Asia, and Africa.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, many 'old' Amsterdammers moved to 'new' cities like Almere and Purmerend, prompted by the third Land-use planning bill of the Dutch Government.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This bill promoted suburbanization and arranged for new developments in so-called "groeikernen", literally *cores of growth*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Young professionals and artists moved into neighborhoods De Pijp and the Jordaan abandoned by these Amsterdammers.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The non-Western immigrants settled mostly in the social housing projects in Amsterdam-West and the Bijlmer.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 2006, people of non-Western origin made up approximately one-fifth of the population of Amsterdam, and more than 30% of the city's children.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A slight majority of the residents of Amsterdam have at least one parent who was born outside the country.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] However, a much larger majority has at least one parent who was born inside the country (intercultural marriages are common in the city).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Only a third of inhabitants under 15 are *autochthons (*person with two parents of Dutch origin).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 2023, *autochthons* were a minority in 40% of Amsterdam's neighborhoods.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Segregation along ethnic lines is visible, with people of non-Western origin, considered a separate group by Statistics Netherlands, concentrating in specific neighborhoods especially in Nieuw-West, Zeeburg, Bijlmer and in certain areas of Amsterdam-Noord.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 2000, Christians formed the largest religious group in the city (28% of the population).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The next largest religion was Islam (8%), most of whose followers were Sunni.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] By 2015, this remained largely unchanged, with a slight decrease in the Muslim population to 7.1%.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has been one of the municipalities in the Netherlands that provided immigrants with extensive and free Dutch-language courses, which have benefited many immigrants.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1578, the largely Catholic city of Amsterdam joined the revolt against Spanish rule, late in comparison to other major northern Dutch cities.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Catholic priests were driven out of the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Following the Dutch takeover, all churches were converted to Protestant worship.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Calvinism was declared the main religion.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] It was forbidden to openly profess Roman Catholicism and the Catholic hierarchy was prohibited until the mid-19th century.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This led to the establishment of clandestine churches, covert religious buildings hidden in pre-existing buildings.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Catholics, some Jews, and dissenting Protestants worshipped in such buildings.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A large influx of foreigners of many religions came to 17th-century Amsterdam, in particular Sephardic Jews from Spain and Portugal, Huguenots from France, Lutherans, Mennonites, as well as Protestants from across the Netherlands.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This led to the establishment of many non-Dutch-speaking churches.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1603, the Jewish received permission to practice their religion in the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1639, the first synagogue was consecrated.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Jews came to call the town "Jerusalem of the West".
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] As they became established in the city, other Christian denominations used converted Catholic chapels to conduct their own services.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The oldest English-language church congregation in the world outside the United Kingdom is found at the Begijnhof.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Regular services there are still offered in English under the auspices of the Church of Scotland.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Being Calvinists, the Huguenots soon integrated into the Dutch Reformed Church, though often retaining their own congregations.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Some, commonly referred to by the moniker 'Walloon', are recognizable today as they offer occasional services in French.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the second half of the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced an influx of Ashkenazim, Jews from Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Jews often fled the pogroms in those areas.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The first Ashkenazis who arrived in Amsterdam were refugees from the Khmelnytsky uprising occurring in Ukraine and the Thirty Years' War, which devastated much of Central Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] They not only founded their own synagogues but had a strong influence on the 'Amsterdam dialect' adding a large Yiddish local vocabulary.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Despite an absence of an official Jewish ghetto, most Jews preferred to live in the eastern part, which used to be the centre of medieval Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The main street of this Jewish neighbourhood was Jodenbreestraat.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhood comprised the Waterlooplein and the Nieuwmarkt.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Buildings in this neighbourhood fell into disrepair after the Second World War a large section of the neighbourhood was demolished during the construction of the metro system.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This led to riots, and as a result, the original plans for large-scale reconstruction were abandoned by the government.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhood was rebuilt with smaller-scale residence buildings based on its original layout.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Catholic churches in Amsterdam have been constructed since the restoration of the episcopal hierarchy in 1853.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] One of the principal architects behind the city's Catholic churches, Cuypers, was also responsible for the Amsterdam Centraal station and the Rijksmuseum.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1924, the Catholic Church hosted the International Eucharistic Congress in Amsterdam; numerous Catholic prelates visited the city, where festivities were held in churches and stadiums.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Catholic processions on the public streets, however, were still forbidden under law at the time.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Only in the 20th century was Amsterdam's relation to Catholicism normalised, but despite its far larger population size, the episcopal see of the city was placed in the provincial town of Haarlem.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Historically, Amsterdam has been predominantly Christian.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In 1900 about 70% of the city's population was Christian; the largest religious denomination was the Dutch Reformed Church, adhered to by about 45% of residents, while members of the Catholic Church formed 25%.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In recent times, the city's religious demography has diversified due to immigration from former colonies.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Hinduism has been introduced by immigrants from Suriname and several distinct branches of Islam have been brought from various parts of the world.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Islam is now the largest non-Christian religion in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The large community of Ghanaian immigrants has established African churches, often in parking garages in the Bijlmer area.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam fans out south from the Amsterdam Centraal station and Damrak, the main street off the station.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The oldest area of the town is known as De Wallen (English: "The Quays").
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] It lies to the east of Damrak and contains the city's famous red-light district.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] To the south of De Wallen is the old Jewish quarter of Waterlooplein.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The medieval and colonial age canals of Amsterdam, known as *grachten*, embraces the heart of the city where homes have interesting gables.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Beyond the Grachtengordel are the former working-class areas of Jordaan and de Pijp.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Museumplein with the city's major museums, the Vondelpark, a 19th-century park named after the Dutch writer Joost van den Vondel, as well as the Plantage neighbourhood, with the zoo, are also located outside the Grachtengordel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Several parts of the city and the surrounding urban area are polders.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This can be recognised by the suffix *-meer* which means *lake*, as in Aalsmeer, Bijlmermeer, Haarlemmermeer and Watergraafsmeer.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Amsterdam canal system is the result of conscious city planning.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the early 17th century, when immigration was at a peak, a comprehensive plan was developed that was based on four concentric half-circles of canals with their ends emerging at the IJ bay.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The fourth and outermost canal is the Singelgracht, which is often not mentioned on maps because it is a collective name for all canals in the outer ring.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Singelgracht should not be confused with the oldest and innermost canal, the Singel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The canals served for defense, water management and transport.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The defenses took the form of a moat and earthen dikes, with gates at transit points, but otherwise no masonry superstructures.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The original plans have been lost, so historians, such as Ed Taverne, need to speculate on the original intentions: it is thought that the considerations of the layout were purely practical and defensive rather than ornamental.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Construction started in 1613 and proceeded from west to east, across the breadth of the layout, like a gigantic windshield wiper as the historian Geert Mak calls it – and not from the centre outwards, as a popular myth has it.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The canal construction in the southern sector was completed by 1656.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Subsequently, the construction of residential buildings proceeded slowly.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The eastern part of the concentric canal plan, covering the area between the Amstel River and the IJ Bay, has never been implemented.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the following centuries, the land was used for parks, senior citizens' homes, theatres, other public facilities, and waterways without much planning.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Over the years, several canals have been filled in, becoming streets or squares, such as the Nieuwezijds Voorburgwal and the Spui.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] After the development of Amsterdam's canals in the 17th century, the city did not grow beyond its borders for two centuries.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] During the 19th century, Samuel Sarphati devised a plan based on the grandeur of Paris and London at that time.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The plan envisaged the construction of new houses, public buildings, and streets just outside the Grachtengordel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The main aim of the plan, however, was to improve public health.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Although the plan did not expand the city, it did produce some of the largest public buildings to date, like the *Paleis voor Volksvlijt*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Following Sarphati, civil engineers Jacobus van Niftrik and Jan Kalff designed an entire ring of 19th-century neighbourhoods surrounding the city's centre, with the city preserving the ownership of all land outside the 17th-century limit, thus firmly controlling development.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Most of these neighbourhoods became home to the working class.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In response to overcrowding, two plans were designed at the beginning of the 20th century which were very different from anything Amsterdam had ever seen before: *Plan Zuid* (designed by the architect Berlage) and *West*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] These plans involved the development of new neighbourhoods consisting of housing blocks for all social classes.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] After the Second World War, large new neighbourhoods were built in the western, southeastern, and northern parts of the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] These new neighbourhoods were built to relieve the city's shortage of living space and give people affordable houses with modern conveniences.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The neighbourhoods consisted mainly of large housing blocks located among green spaces, connected to wide roads, making the neighbourhoods accessible by motor car.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The western suburbs which were built in that period are collectively called the Westelijke Tuinsteden.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The area to the southeast of the city built during the same period is known as the Bijlmer.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has a rich architectural history.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The oldest building in Amsterdam is the Oude Kerk (English: Old Church), at the heart of the Wallen, consecrated in 1306.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The oldest wooden building is *Het Houten Huys* at the Begijnhof.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] It was constructed around 1425 and is one of only two existing wooden buildings.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] It is also one of the few examples of Gothic architecture in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The oldest stone building in the Netherlands, The Moriaan is built in 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the 16th century, wooden buildings were razed and replaced with brick ones.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] During this period, many buildings were constructed in the architectural style of the Renaissance.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Buildings of this period are very recognisable with their stepped gable façades, which is the common Dutch Renaissance style.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam quickly developed its own Renaissance architecture.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] These buildings were built according to the principles of the architect Hendrick de Keyser.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] One of the most striking buildings designed by Hendrick de Keyser is the Westerkerk.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the 17th century baroque architecture became very popular, as it was elsewhere in Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This roughly coincided with Amsterdam's Golden Age.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The leading architects of this style in Amsterdam were Jacob van Campen, Philips Vingboons and Daniel Stalpaert.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Philip Vingboons designed splendid merchants' houses throughout the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A famous building in baroque style in Amsterdam is the Royal Palace on Dam Square.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Throughout the 18th century, Amsterdam was heavily influenced by French culture.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] This is reflected in the architecture of that period.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Around 1815, architects broke with the baroque style and started building in different neo-styles.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Most Gothic style buildings date from that era and are therefore said to be built in a neo-gothic style.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] At the end of the 19th century, the Jugendstil or Art Nouveau style became popular and many new buildings were constructed in this architectural style.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Since Amsterdam expanded rapidly during this period, new buildings adjacent to the city centre were also built in this style.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The houses in the vicinity of the Museum Square in Amsterdam Oud-Zuid are an example of Jugendstil.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The last style that was popular in Amsterdam before the modern era was Art Deco.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam had its own version of the style, which was called the Amsterdamse School.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Whole districts were built in this style, such as the *Rivierenbuurt*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] A notable feature of the façades of buildings designed in Amsterdamse School is that they are highly decorated and ornate, with oddly shaped windows and doors.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The old city centre is the focal point of all the architectural styles before the end of the 19th century.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Jugendstil and Georgian are mostly found outside the city centre in the neighbourhoods built in the early 20th century, although there are also some striking examples of these styles in the city centre.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Most historic buildings in the city centre and nearby are houses, such as the famous merchants' houses lining the canals.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Amsterdam has many parks, open spaces, and squares throughout the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Vondelpark, the largest park in the city, is located in the Oud-Zuid neighbourhood and is named after the 17th-century Amsterdam author Joost van den Vondel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Yearly, the park has around 10 million visitors.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the park is an open-air theatre, a playground, and several horeca facilities.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] In the Zuid borough, is the Beatrixpark, named after Queen Beatrix.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Between Amsterdam and Amstelveen is the Amsterdamse Bos ("Amsterdam Forest"), the largest recreational area in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Annually, almost 4.5 million people visit the park, which has a size of 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres) and is approximately three times the size of Central Park.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The Amstelpark in the Zuid borough houses the Rieker windmill, which dates to 1636.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Other parks include the Sarphatipark in the De Pijp neighbourhood, the Oosterpark in the Oost borough and the Westerpark in the Westerpark neighbourhood.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city has three beaches: Nemo Beach, Citybeach "Het stenen hoofd" (Silodam), and Blijburg, all located in the Centrum borough.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The city has many open squares (*plein* in Dutch).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] The namesake of the city as the site of the original dam, Dam Square, is the main city square and has the Royal Palace and National Monument.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Museumplein hosts various museums, including the Rijksmuseum, Van Gogh Museum, and Stedelijk Museum.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p01] Other squares include Rembrandtplein, Muntplein, Nieuwmarkt, Leidseplein, Spui and Waterlooplein.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is the financial and business capital of the Netherlands.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] A substantial number of large corporations and banks' headquarters are located in the Amsterdam area, including: AkzoNobel, Heineken International, ING Group, ABN AMRO, TomTom, Delta Lloyd Group, Booking.com and Philips.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Although many small offices remain along the historic canals, centrally based companies have increasingly relocated outside Amsterdam's city centre.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The adjoining municipality of Amstelveen is the location of KPMG International's global headquarters.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Other non-Dutch companies have chosen to settle in communities surrounding Amsterdam since they allow freehold property ownership, whereas Amsterdam retains ground rent.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange (AEX), now part of Euronext, is the world's oldest stock exchange and, due to Brexit, has overtaken LSE as the largest bourse in Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It is near Dam Square in the city centre.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Port of Amsterdam is the fourth-largest port in Europe, the 38th largest port in the world, and the second-largest port in the Netherlands by metric tons of cargo.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2014, the Port of Amsterdam had a cargo throughput of 97,4 million tons of cargo, which was mostly bulk cargo.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has the biggest cruise port in the Netherlands with more than 150 cruise ships every year.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2019, the new lock in IJmuiden opened; since then, the port has been able to grow to 125 million tonnes in capacity.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is one of the most popular tourist destinations in Europe, receiving more than 5.34 million international visitors annually; this is excluding the 16 million day-trippers visiting the city every year.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The number of visitors has been growing steadily over the past decade.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This can be attributed to an increasing number of European visitors.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Two-thirds of the hotels are located in the city's centre.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Hotels with four or five stars contribute 42% of the total beds available and 41% of the overnight stays in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The room occupation rate was 85% in 2017, up from 78% in 2006.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The majority of tourists (74%) originate from Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The largest group of non-European visitors come from the United States, accounting for 14% of the total.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Certain years have a theme in Amsterdam to attract extra tourists.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] For example, the year 2006 was designated "Rembrandt 400", to celebrate the 400th birthday of Rembrandt van Rijn.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Some hotels offer special arrangements or activities during these years.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The average number of guests per year staying at the four campsites around the city ranges from 12,000 to 65,000.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2023, the city began running a campaign to dissuade British men between the ages of 18 and 35 from coming to the city as tourists.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The ad shows young men being handcuffed by police and is part of a new campaign to clean up the city's reputation.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] On 25 May 2023, in a bid to crackdown on wild tourist behaviour, the city banned weed smoking in public areas in and around the red light district.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] De Wallen, also known as Walletjes or Rosse Buurt, is a designated area for legalised prostitution and is Amsterdam's largest and best-known red-light district.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This neighbourhood has become a famous attraction for tourists.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It consists of a network of canals, streets, and alleys containing several hundred small, one-room apartments rented by sex workers who offer their services from behind a window or glass door, typically illuminated with red lights.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In recent years, the city government has been closing and repurposing the famous red-light district windows to clean up the area and reduce the amount of party and sex tourism.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Shops in Amsterdam range from large high-end department stores such as De Bijenkorf founded in 1870 to small specialty shops.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's high-end shops are found in the streets P.C.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Hooftstraat and *Cornelis Schuytstraat*, which are located in the vicinity of the Vondelpark.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] One of Amsterdam's busiest high streets is the narrow, medieval Kalverstraat in the heart of the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Other shopping areas include the *Negen Straatjes* and Haarlemmerdijk and Haarlemmerstraat.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] *Negen Straatjes* are nine narrow streets within the *Grachtengordel*, the concentric canal system of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Negen Straatjes differ from other shopping districts with the presence of a large diversity of privately owned shops.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Haarlemmerstraat and Haarlemmerdijk were voted the best shopping street in the Netherlands in 2011.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] These streets have as the *Negen Straatjes* a large diversity of privately owned shops.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The city also features a large number of open-air markets such as the Albert Cuyp Market, Westerstraat-markt, Ten Katemarkt, and Dappermarkt.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Some of these markets are held daily, like the Albert Cuypmarkt and the Dappermarkt.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Others, like the Westerstraatmarkt, are held every week.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Several fashion brands and designers are based in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Fashion designers include Iris van Herpen, Mart Visser, Viktor & Rolf, Marlies Dekkers and Frans Molenaar.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Fashion models like Yfke Sturm, Doutzen Kroes and Kim Noorda started their careers in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has its garment centre in the World Fashion Center.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Fashion photographers Inez van Lamsweerde and Vinoodh Matadin were born in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] During the later part of the 16th century, Amsterdam's Rederijkerskamer (Chamber of rhetoric) organised contests between different Chambers in the reading of poetry and drama.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 1637, Schouwburg, the first theatre in Amsterdam was built, opening on 3 January 1638.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The first ballet performances in the Netherlands were given in Schouwburg in 1642 with the *Ballet of the Five Senses*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In the 18th century, French theatre became popular.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] While Amsterdam was under the influence of German music in the 19th century there were few national opera productions; the Hollandse Opera of Amsterdam was built in 1888 for the specific purpose of promoting Dutch opera.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In the 19th century, popular culture was centred on the Nes area in Amsterdam (mainly vaudeville and music-hall).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] An improved metronome was invented in 1812 by Dietrich Nikolaus Winkel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum (1885) and Stedelijk Museum (1895) were built and opened.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 1888, the Concertgebouworkest orchestra was established.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] With the 20th century came cinema, radio and television.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Though most studios are located in Hilversum and Aalsmeer, Amsterdam's influence on programming is very strong.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Many people who work in the television industry live in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Also, the headquarters of the Dutch SBS Broadcasting Group is located in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] There are also a number of cultural centers based in the city that produce public programs about the arts, sciences, politics and history, including de Balie and the John Adams Institute.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The most important museums of Amsterdam are located on the Museumplein (Museum Square), located at the southwestern side of the Rijksmuseum.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It was created in the last quarter of the 19th century on the grounds of the former World's fair.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The northeastern part of the square is bordered by the large Rijksmuseum.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In front of the Rijksmuseum on the square itself is a long, rectangular pond.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This is transformed into an ice rink in winter.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The northwestern part of the square is bordered by the Van Gogh Museum, House of Bols Cocktail & Genever Experience and Coster Diamonds.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The southwestern border of the Museum Square is the Van Baerlestraat, which is a major thoroughfare in this part of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Concertgebouw is located across this street from the square.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] To the southeast of the square are several large houses, one of which contains the American consulate.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] A parking garage can be found underneath the square, as well as a supermarket.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Museumplein is covered almost entirely with a lawn, except for the northeastern part of the square which is covered with gravel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The current appearance of the square was realised in 1999 when the square was remodelled.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The square itself is the most prominent site in Amsterdam for festivals and outdoor concerts, especially in the summer.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Plans were made in 2008 to remodel the square again because many inhabitants of Amsterdam are not happy with its current appearance.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum possesses the largest and most important collection of classical Dutch art.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Its collection consists of nearly one million objects.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The artist most associated with Amsterdam is Rembrandt, whose work, and the work of his pupils, is displayed in the Rijksmuseum.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Rembrandt's masterpiece *The Night Watch* is one of the top pieces of art in the museum.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It also houses paintings from artists like Bartholomeus van der Helst, Johannes Vermeer, Frans Hals, Ferdinand Bol, Albert Cuyp, Jacob van Ruisdael and Paulus Potter.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Aside from paintings, the collection consists of a large variety of decorative art.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This ranges from Delftware to giant doll-houses from the 17th century.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The architect of the gothic revival building was P.J.H.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The museum underwent a 10-year, 375 million euro renovation starting in 2003.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The full collection was reopened to the public on 13 April 2013.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Rijksmuseum has remained the most visited museum in Amsterdam with 2.4 million visitors in 2024.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Van Gogh lived in Amsterdam for a short while and there is a museum dedicated to his work.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The museum is housed in one of the few modern buildings in this area of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The building was designed by Gerrit Rietveld.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This building is where the permanent collection is displayed.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] A new building was added to the museum in 1999.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This building, known as the performance wing, was designed by Japanese architect Kisho Kurokawa.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Its purpose is to house temporary exhibitions of the museum.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Some of Van Gogh's most famous paintings, like *The Potato Eaters* and *Sunflowers*, are in the collection.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Van Gogh museum is the second most visited museum in Amsterdam, not far behind the Rijksmuseum in terms of the number of visits, being approximately 1.8 million in 2024.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Next to the Van Gogh Museum stands the Stedelijk Museum.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This is Amsterdam's most important museum of modern art.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The museum is as old as the square it borders and was opened in 1895.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The permanent collection consists of works of art from artists like Piet Mondrian, Karel Appel, and Kazimir Malevich.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] After renovations lasting several years, the museum opened in September 2012 with a new composite extension that has been called 'The Bathtub' due to its resemblance to one.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam contains many other museums throughout the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The modern-styled Nemo is dedicated to child-friendly science exhibitions.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's musical culture includes a large collection of songs that treat the city nostalgically and lovingly.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The 1949 song "Aan de Amsterdamse grachten" ("On the canals of Amsterdam") was performed and recorded by many artists, including John Kraaijkamp Sr.; the best-known version is probably that by Wim Sonneveld (1962).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In the 1950s Johnny Jordaan rose to fame with "Geef mij maar Amsterdam" ("I prefer Amsterdam"), which praises the city above all others (explicitly Paris); Jordaan sang especially about his own neighbourhood, the Jordaan ("Bij ons in de Jordaan").
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Colleagues and contemporaries of Johnny include Tante Leen and Manke Nelis.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Another notable Amsterdam song is "Amsterdam" by Jacques Brel (1964).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] A 2011 poll by Amsterdam newspaper *Het Parool* that Trio Bier's "Oude Wolf" was voted "Amsterdams lijflied".
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Notable Amsterdam bands from the modern era include the Osdorp Posse and the Ex.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] AFAS Live (formerly known as the Heineken Music Hall) is a concert hall located near the Johan Cruyff Arena (known as the Amsterdam Arena until 2018).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Its main purpose is to serve as a podium for pop concerts for big audiences.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Many famous international artists have performed there.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Two other notable venues, Paradiso and the Melkweg are located near the Leidseplein.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Both focus on broad programming, ranging from indie rock to hip-hop, R&B, and other popular genres.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Other subcultural music venues are OCCII, OT301, De Nieuwe Anita, Winston Kingdom, and Zaal 100.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Jazz has a strong following in Amsterdam, with the Bimhuis being the premier venue.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2012, Ziggo Dome was opened, also near Amsterdam Arena, a state-of-the-art indoor music arena.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] AFAS Live is also host to many electronic dance music festivals, alongside many other venues.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Armin van Buuren and Tiesto, some of the world's leading Trance DJs hail from the Netherlands and frequently perform in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Each year in October, the city hosts the Amsterdam Dance Event (ADE) which is one of the leading electronic music conferences and one of the biggest club festivals for electronic music in the world, attracting over 350,000 visitors each year.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Another popular dance festival is 5daysoff, which takes place in the venues Paradiso and Melkweg.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In the summertime, there are several big outdoor dance parties in or nearby Amsterdam, such as Awakenings, Dance Valley, Mystery Land, Loveland, A Day at the Park, Welcome to the Future, and Valtifest.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has a world-class symphony orchestra, the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Their home is the Concertgebouw, which is across the Van Baerlestraat from the Museum Square.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It is considered by critics to be a concert hall with some of the best acoustics in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The building contains three halls, Grote Zaal, Kleine Zaal, and Spiegelzaal.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Some nine hundred concerts and other events per year take place in the Concertgebouw, for a public of over 700,000, making it one of the most-visited concert halls in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The opera house of Amsterdam is located adjacent to the city hall.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Therefore, the two buildings combined are often called the Stopera, (a word originally coined by protesters against its very construction: *Stop the Opera[-house]*).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This huge modern complex, opened in 1986, lies in the former Jewish neighbourhood at *Waterlooplein* next to the river Amstel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The *Stopera* is the home base of Dutch National Opera, Dutch National Ballet and the Holland Symfonia.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Muziekgebouw aan 't IJ is a concert hall, which is located in the IJ near the central station.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Its concerts perform mostly modern classical music.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Located adjacent to it, is the *Bimhuis*, a concert hall for improvised and jazz music.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has three main theatre buildings.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Stadsschouwburg at the Leidseplein is the home base of Toneelgroep Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Most plays are performed in the Grote Zaal (Great Hall).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The normal program of events encompasses all sorts of theatrical forms.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2009, the new hall of the Stadsschouwburg Amsterdam, Toneelgroep Amsterdam, and Melkweg opened, and the renovation of the front end of the theatre was ready.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Dutch National Opera and Ballet (formerly known as *Het Muziektheater*), dating from 1986, is the principal opera house and home to Dutch National Opera and Dutch National Ballet.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Royal Theatre Carré was built as a permanent circus theatre in 1887 and is currently mainly used for musicals, cabaret performances, and pop concerts.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The recently re-opened DeLaMar Theater houses more commercial plays and musicals.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] A new theatre has also moved into the Amsterdam scene in 2014, joining other established venues: Theater Amsterdam is located in the west part of Amsterdam, on the Danzigerkade.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It is housed in a modern building with a panoramic view over the harbour.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The theatre is the first-ever purpose-built venue to showcase a single play entitled ANNE, the play based on Anne Frank's life.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] On the east side of town, there is a small theatre in a converted bathhouse, the Badhuistheater.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The theatre often has English programming.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Netherlands has a tradition of cabaret or *kleinkunst*, which combines music, storytelling, commentary, theatre, and comedy.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Cabaret dates back to the 1930s and artists like Wim Kan, Wim Sonneveld, and Toon Hermans were pioneers of this form of art in the Netherlands.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In Amsterdam are the Kleinkunstacademie (English: Cabaret Academy) and Nederlied Kleinkunstkoor (English: Cabaret Choir).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Contemporary popular artists are Youp van 't Hek, Freek de Jonge, Herman Finkers, Hans Teeuwen, Theo Maassen, Herman van Veen, Najib Amhali, Raoul Heertje, Jörgen Raymann, Brigitte Kaandorp and Comedytrain.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The English-spoken comedy scene was established with the founding of Boom Chicago in 1993.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] They have their own theatre at Leidseplein.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is famous for its vibrant and diverse nightlife.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] They range from large and modern to small and cosy.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The typical *Bruine Kroeg* (brown *café*) breathes a more old-fashioned atmosphere with dimmed lights, candles, and somewhat older clientele.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] These brown cafés mostly offer a wide range of local and international artisanal beers.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Most *cafés* have terraces in summertime.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] A common sight on the Leidseplein during summer is a square full of terraces packed with people drinking beer or wine.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Many restaurants can be found in Amsterdam as well.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Since Amsterdam is a multicultural city, a lot of different ethnic restaurants can be found.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Restaurants range from being rather luxurious and expensive to being ordinary and affordable.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam also possesses many discothèques.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The two main nightlife areas for tourists are the Leidseplein and the Rembrandtplein.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Paradiso, Melkweg and Sugar Factory are cultural centres, which turn into discothèques on some nights.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2008, there were 140 festivals and events in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] During the same year, Amsterdam was designated as the World Book Capital for one year by UNESCO.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] On Koningsdag—which is held each year on 27 April—hundreds of thousands of people travel to Amsterdam to celebrate with the city's residents.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The entire city becomes overcrowded with people buying products from the *free market*, or visiting one of the many music concerts.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The yearly Holland Festival attracts international artists and visitors from all over Europe.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Gay Pride is a yearly local LGBT parade of boats in Amsterdam's canals, held on the first Saturday in August.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The annual Uitmarkt is a three-day cultural event at the start of the cultural season in late August.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It offers previews of many different artists, such as musicians and poets, who perform on podia.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is home of the *Eredivisie* football club AFC Ajax.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The stadium Johan Cruyff Arena is the home of Ajax.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It is located in the south-east of the city next to the new Amsterdam Bijlmer ArenA railway station.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Before moving to their current location in 1996, Ajax played their regular matches in the now demolished De Meer Stadion in the eastern part of the city or in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 1928, Amsterdam hosted the Summer Olympics.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Olympic Stadium built for the occasion has been completely restored and is now used for cultural and sporting events, such as the Amsterdam Marathon.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 1920, Amsterdam assisted in hosting some of the sailing events for the Summer Olympics held in neighbouring Antwerp, Belgium by hosting events at Buiten IJ.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] They had also made a bid to host the 1952 and 1992 Summer Olympics but lost to Helsinki and Barcelona.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The city holds the Dam to Dam Run, a 16 km (10 mi) race from Amsterdam to Zaandam, as well as the Amsterdam Marathon.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The ice hockey team Amstel Tijgers plays in the Jaap Eden ice rink.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The team competes in the Dutch Ice Hockey Premier League.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Speed skating championships have been held on the 400-meter lane of this ice rink.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam holds two American football franchises: the Amsterdam Crusaders and the Amsterdam Panthers.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Pirates baseball team competes in the Dutch Major League.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] There are three field hockey teams: Amsterdam, Pinoké, and Hurley, who play their matches around the Wagener Stadium in the nearby city of Amstelveen.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The basketball team MyGuide Amsterdam competes in the Dutch premier division and play their games in the Sporthallen Zuid.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] There is one rugby club in Amsterdam, which also hosts sports training classes such as RTC (Rugby Talenten Centrum or Rugby Talent Centre) and the National Rugby Stadium.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Since 1999, the city of Amsterdam honours the best sportsmen and women at the Amsterdam Sports Awards.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Boxer Raymond Joval and field hockey midfielder Carole Thate were the first to receive the awards, in 1999.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam hosted the World Gymnaestrada in 1991 and will do so again in 2023.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The city of Amsterdam is a municipality under the Dutch Municipalities Act.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It is governed by a directly elected municipal council, a municipal executive, and a mayor.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Since 1981, the municipality of Amsterdam has gradually been divided into semi-autonomous boroughs, called *stadsdelen* or 'districts'.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Over time, a total of 15 boroughs were created.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] As with all Dutch municipalities, Amsterdam is governed by a directly elected municipal council, a municipal executive and a government appointed mayor (*burgemeester*).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The mayor is a member of the municipal executive board but also has individual responsibilities in maintaining public order.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] She replaces Eberhard van der Laan (Labour Party) who was the Mayor of Amsterdam from 2010 until his death in October 2017.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] After the 2014 municipal council elections, a governing majority of D66, VVD and SP was formed – the first coalition without the Labour Party since World War II.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Next to the mayor, the municipal executive consists of eight *wethouders* ('alderpersons') appointed by the municipal council: four D66 alderpersons, two VVD alderpersons and two SP alderpersons.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] On 18 September 2017, it was announced by Eberhard van der Laan in an open letter to Amsterdam citizens that Kajsa Ollongren would take up his office as acting Mayor of Amsterdam with immediate effect due to ill health.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Ollongren was succeeded as acting Mayor by Eric van der Burg on 26 October 2017 and by Jozias van Aartsen on 4 December 2017.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Unlike most other Dutch municipalities, Amsterdam is subdivided into seven boroughs, called *stadsdelen* or 'districts', and the urban area of Weesp.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This system was gradually implemented in the 1980s to improve local governance.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The boroughs are responsible for many activities that had previously been run by the central city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2010, the number of Amsterdam boroughs reached fifteen.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Fourteen of those had their own district council (*deelraad*), elected by a popular vote.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The fifteenth, Westpoort, covers the harbour of Amsterdam and has very few residents.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Therefore, it was governed by the central municipal council.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Under the borough system, municipal decisions are made at the borough level, except for those affairs on the whole city such as major infrastructure projects, which are the jurisdiction of the central municipal authorities.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2010, the borough system was restructured, in which many smaller boroughs merged into larger boroughs.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2014, under a reform of the Dutch Municipalities Act, the Amsterdam boroughs lost much of their autonomous status, as their district councils were abolished.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The municipal council of Amsterdam voted to maintain the borough system by replacing the district councils with smaller, but still directly elected district committees (*bestuurscommissies*).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Under a municipal ordinance, the new district committees were granted responsibilities through the delegation of regulatory and executive powers by the central municipal council.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] "Amsterdam" is usually understood to refer to the municipality of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Colloquially, some areas within the municipality, such as the town of Durgerdam, may not be considered part of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The Amsterdam Department for Research and Statistics uses a fourth conurbation, namely the *Stadsregio Amsterdam* ('City Region of Amsterdam').
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The city region is similar to Greater Amsterdam but includes the municipalities of Zaanstad and Wormerland.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The smallest of these areas is the municipality of Amsterdam with a population of about 870,000 in 2021.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The larger conurbation had a population of over one million.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It includes the municipalities of Zaanstad, Wormerland, Oostzaan, Diemen, and Amstelveen only, as well as the municipality of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Greater Amsterdam includes 15 municipalities and had a population of 1,400,000 in 2021.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Though much larger in area, the population of this area is only slightly larger, because the definition excludes the relatively populous municipality of Zaanstad.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The largest area by population, the Metropolitan Region Amsterdam (Dutch: Metropoolregio Amsterdam), has a population of 2,33 million.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It includes for instance Zaanstad, Wormerland, Muiden, Abcoude, Haarlem, Almere and Lelystad but excludes Graft-De Rijp.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is part of the conglomerate metropolitan area Randstad, with a total population of 6,659,300 inhabitants.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Of these various metropolitan area configurations, only the *Stadsregio Amsterdam* (City Region of Amsterdam) has a formal governmental status.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Its responsibilities include regional spatial planning and metropolitan public transport concessions.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Under the Dutch Constitution, Amsterdam is the capital of the Netherlands.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Since the 1983 constitutional revision, the constitution mentions "Amsterdam" and "capital" in chapter 2, article 32: The king's confirmation by oath and his coronation take place in "the capital Amsterdam" ("*de hoofdstad Amsterdam*").
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Previous versions of the constitution only mentioned "the city of Amsterdam" ("*de stad Amsterdam*").
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] For a royal investiture, therefore, the States General of the Netherlands (the Dutch Parliament) meets for a ceremonial joint session in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The ceremony traditionally takes place at the Nieuwe Kerk on Dam Square, immediately after the former monarch has signed the act of abdication at the nearby Royal Palace of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Normally, however, the Parliament sits in The Hague, the city which has historically been the seat of the Dutch government, the Dutch monarchy, and the Dutch supreme court.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Foreign embassies are also located in The Hague.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The coat of arms of Amsterdam is composed of several historical elements.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] First and centre are three St Andrew's crosses, aligned in a vertical band on the city's shield (although Amsterdam's patron saint was Saint Nicholas).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] These St Andrew's crosses can also be found on the city shields of neighbours Amstelveen and Ouder-Amstel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This part of the coat of arms is the basis of the flag of Amsterdam, flown by the city government, but also as civil ensign for ships registered in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Second is the Imperial Crown of Austria.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 1489, out of gratitude for services and loans, Maximilian I awarded Amsterdam the right to adorn its coat of arms with the king's crown.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Then, in 1508, this was replaced with Maximilian's imperial crown when he was crowned Holy Roman Emperor.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In the early years of the 17th century, Maximilian's crown in Amsterdam's coat of arms was again replaced, this time with the crown of Emperor Rudolph II, a crown that became the Imperial Crown of Austria.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The lions date from the late 16th century, when the city and province became part of the Republic of the Seven United Netherlands.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Last came the city's official motto: *Heldhaftig, Vastberaden, Barmhartig* ("Heroic, Determined, Merciful"), bestowed on the city in 1947 by Queen Wilhelmina, in recognition of the city's bravery during the Second World War.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Currently, there are sixteen tram routes and five metro routes.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] All are operated by the municipal public transport operator Gemeentelijk Vervoerbedrijf (GVB), which also runs the city bus network.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Four fare-free GVB ferries carry pedestrians and cyclists across the IJ lake to the borough of Amsterdam-Noord, and two fare-charging ferries run east and west along the harbour.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] There are also privately operated water taxis, a water bus, a boat-sharing operation, electric rental boats, and canal cruises, that transport people along Amsterdam's waterways.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Regional buses, and some suburban buses, are operated by Connexxion and EBS.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] International coach services are provided by FlixBus and BlaBlaCar Bus.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] To facilitate easier transport to the centre of Amsterdam, the city has various P+R Locations where people can park their car at an affordable price and transfer to one of the numerous public transport lines.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam was intended in 1932 to be the hub, a kind of Kilometre Zero, of the highway system of the Netherlands, with freeways numbered One to Eight planned to originate from the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The outbreak of the Second World War and shifting priorities led to the current situation, where only roads A1, A2, and A4 originate from Amsterdam according to the original plan.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The A3 to Rotterdam was cancelled in 1970 to conserve the Groene Hart.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Road A8, leading north to Zaandam and the A10 Ringroad were opened between 1968 and 1974.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Besides the A1, A2, A4 and A8, several freeways, such as the A7 and A6, carry traffic mainly bound for Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The A10 ringroad surrounding the city connects Amsterdam with the Dutch national network of freeways.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Interchanges on the A10 allow cars to enter the city by transferring to one of the 18 *city roads*, numbered S101 through to S118.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] These city roads are regional roads without grade separation, and sometimes without a central reservation.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The S100 *Centrumring* is a smaller ring road circumnavigating the city's centre.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In the city centre, driving a car is discouraged.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Parking fees are expensive, and many streets are closed to cars or are one-way.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The local government sponsors carsharing and carpooling initiatives such as *Autodelen* and *Meerijden.nu*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The local government has also started removing parking spaces in the city in 2019, with the goal of removing 10,000 spaces (roughly 1,500 per year) by 2025.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is served by ten stations of the Nederlandse Spoorwegen (Dutch Railways).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Five are intercity stops: Sloterdijk, Zuid, Amstel, Bijlmer ArenA and Amsterdam Centraal.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The stations for local services are: Lelylaan, RAI, Holendrecht, Muiderpoort and Science Park.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Centraal is also an international railway station.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] From the station, there are regular services to destinations such as Austria, Belgium, Czech Republic, France, Germany, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Among these trains are international trains of the Nederlandse Spoorwegen and Deutsche Bahn to Berlin, Eurostar services to Antwerp, Brussels, Paris and London and ICE services to Cologne and Frankfurt.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam Airport Schiphol is less than 20 minutes by train from Amsterdam Centraal station and is served by domestic and international intercity trains, such as Eurostar and EuroCity.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Schiphol is the largest airport in the Netherlands, the third-largest in Europe, and the 14th-largest in the world in terms of passengers.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] It handles over 68 million passengers per year and is the home base of four airlines, KLM, Transavia, Martinair and Arkefly.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] As of 2014, Schiphol was the fifth busiest airport in the world measured by international passenger numbers.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This airport is 4 meters below sea level.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Although Schiphol is internationally known as Amsterdam Schiphol Airport it lies in the neighbouring municipality of Haarlemmermeer, southwest of the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Rotterdam The Hague Airport, a smaller international airport, is also within an hour's drive of the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is one of the most bicycle-friendly large cities in the world and is a centre of bicycle culture with good facilities for cyclists such as bike paths and bike racks, and several guarded bike storage garages (*fietsenstalling*) which can be used.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] According to the most recent figures published by the Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS), in 2015 the 442,693 households (850,000 residents) in Amsterdam together owned 847,000 bicycles – 1.91 bicycles per household.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Theft is widespread—in 2011, about 83,000 bicycles were stolen in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Bicycles are used by all socio-economic groups because of their convenience, Amsterdam's small size, the 400 km (249 mi) of bike paths, the flat terrain, and the inconvenience of driving an automobile.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam has two universities: the University of Amsterdam (*Universiteit van Amsterdam*, UvA), and the *Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam* (VU).
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The University of Amsterdam is home to Room for Discussion, an independent interview platform that has welcomed a variety of prominent guests including Christine Lagarde, Mario Draghi, Charles Michel, Rob Bauer, and Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Other institutions for higher education include an art school – Gerrit Rietveld Academie, a university of applied sciences – the Hogeschool van Amsterdam, and the Amsterdamse Hogeschool voor de Kunsten.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's International Institute of Social History is one of the world's largest documentary and research institutions concerning social history, and especially the history of the labour movement.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam's Hortus Botanicus, founded in the early 17th century, is one of the oldest botanical gardens in the world, with many old and rare specimens, among them the coffee plant that served as the parent for the entire coffee culture in Central and South America.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] There are over 200 primary schools in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Some of these primary schools base their teachings on particular pedagogic theories like the various Montessori schools.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The biggest Montessori high school in Amsterdam is the Montessori Lyceum Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Many schools, however, are based on religion.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] This used to be primarily Roman Catholicism and various Protestant denominations, but with the influx of Muslim immigrants, there has been a rise in the number of Islamic schools.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Jewish schools can be found in the southern suburbs of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is noted for having five independent grammar schools (Dutch: gymnasia), the Vossius Gymnasium, Barlaeus Gymnasium, St.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Ignatius Gymnasium, Het 4e Gymnasium and the Cygnus Gymnasium where a classical curriculum including Latin and classical Greek is taught.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Though believed until recently by many to be an anachronistic and elitist concept that would soon die out, the gymnasia have recently experienced a revival, leading to the formation of a fourth and fifth grammar school in which the three aforementioned schools participate.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Most secondary schools in Amsterdam offer a variety of different levels of education in the same school.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The city also has various colleges ranging from art and design to politics and economics which are mostly also available for students coming from other countries.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is a prominent centre for national and international media.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is home to the second-largest Dutch commercial TV group SBS Broadcasting Group, consisting of TV stations SBS6, Net5, and Veronica.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] However, Amsterdam is not considered 'the media city of the Netherlands'.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The town of Hilversum, 30 km (19 mi) south-east of Amsterdam, has been crowned with this unofficial title.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Hilversum is the principal centre for radio and television broadcasting in the Netherlands.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Radio Netherlands, heard worldwide via shortwave radio since the 1920s, is also based there.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Hilversum is home to an extensive complex of audio and television studios belonging to the national broadcast production company NOS, as well as to the studios and offices of all the Dutch public broadcasting organisations and many commercial TV production companies.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2012, the music video for "Live My Life" by Far East Movement was filmed in various parts of Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Several movies have been filmed in Amsterdam, including the James Bond film *Diamonds Are Forever*, *Ocean's Twelve*, *Girl with a Pearl Earring*, *Kidnapping Mr.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Heineken*, *Layer Cake* and *The Hitman's Bodyguard*.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam is also featured in John Green's book *The Fault in Our Stars*, which was made into a film that also partly takes place in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] In 2003, the British drama series *Bad Girls* filmed scenes on location in Amsterdam.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] The scenes shows the male officers on a weekend trip in the red light district where they encounter escapee Shell Dockley and return her to the UK.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam appears as a multiplayer map in *Modern Warfare II* under the name Breenbergh Hotel.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] Amsterdam also appears in *Black Ops Cold War* in an update, having players fight through the city.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] From the late 1960s onwards many buildings in Amsterdam have been squatted both for housing and for use as social centres.
[src:adam-kendon/amsterdam-p02] A number of these squats have legalised and become well known, such as OCCII, OT301, Paradiso and Vrankrijk.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The **Annenberg School for Communication** is the communication school at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The school was established in 1958 by Wharton School alumnus Walter Annenberg as the Annenberg School of Communications.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The name was changed to its current title in 1990.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Walter Annenberg founded the Annenberg School of Communication at the University of Pennsylvania in 1958.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The school, whose first class began in 1959, was initially a master's-only program.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The first Annenberg students were admitted in the Fall semester of 1959 and graduated in the Spring semester of 1960.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Gilbert Seldes was the first dean at the school, serving from 1959 until 1963.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] George Gerbner, an advisor to communications commissions and a major contributor to cultivation theory, became dean in 1964.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] He founded the Cultural Indicators Project in 1967, measuring trends in television content and how it shaped perceptions of society.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The Annenberg School launched its doctoral program in 1968.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The school retained ownership of the *Journal of Communication* from 1974 to 1991, which was published by Penn while Gerbner was editor.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Dean George Gerbner held the post until 1989.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Kathleen Hall Jamieson was dean from 1989 to 2003.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 1989, the Annenberg School and Oxford University Press published the four-volume *International Encyclopedia of Communications*, the first broad-based attempt to survey the entire communication field.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 1990, the school changed its name to **Annenberg School for Communication**.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] During Jamieson's deanship, the school received two large endowments from the Annenberg Foundation.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 1993, Walter and Leonore Annenberg, through their foundation, granted Penn $120 million to endow the school and establish the Annenberg Public Policy Center.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 2002, the Annenberg Foundation gave $100 million to the school for scholarships, faculty chairs, and classroom refurbishment.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Also during this time, the Annenberg School ended its master's program, with prospective students only being able to apply to their doctoral program.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] After Jamieson stepped down as dean in 2003, the school named Michael X.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Delli Carpini's term was extended until 2018.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 2019, John Jackson became the new dean at Annenberg.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] In 2024, while in office, President Joe Biden expressed his desire to return to the Penn Biden Center for Diplomacy and Global Engagement after leaving the White House.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Annenberg School offers a five-year doctoral program.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] Annenberg also offers a joint doctoral degree in communication and political science.
[src:adam-kendon/annenberg-school-for-communication-at-the-university-of-pennsylvania] The school hosts postdoctoral fellowships and visiting scholars.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:adam-kendon/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] Many Australian Aboriginal cultures have or traditionally had a manually coded language, a signed counterpart of their oral language.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] There is some similarity between neighbouring groups and some contact pidgin similar to Plains Indian Sign Language in the American Great Plains.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] Sign languages appear to be most developed in areas with the most extensive speech taboos: the central desert (particularly among the Warlpiri and Warumungu), and western Cape York.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] Complex gestural systems have also been reported in the southern, central, and western desert regions, the Gulf of Carpentaria (including north-east Arnhem Land and the Tiwi Islands), some Torres Strait Islands, and the southern regions of the Fitzmaurice and Kimberley areas.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] Evidence for sign languages elsewhere is slim, but they have been noted as far south as the south coast (Jaralde Sign Language) and there are even some accounts from the first few years of the 20th century of the use of sign by people from the south west coast.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] However, many of the codes are now extinct, and very few accounts have recorded any detail.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] However, an Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander dialect of Auslan exists in Far North Queensland (extending from Yarrabah to Cape York), which is heavily influenced by the indigenous sign languages and gestural systems of the region.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] Sign languages were noted in north Queensland as early as 1908 (Roth).
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] Early research into indigenous sign was done by the American linguist La Mont West, and later, in more depth, by English linguist Adam Kendon.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] Miriwoong Sign Language is also a developed or perhaps highly developed language.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-aboriginal-sign-languages] With the decline of Aboriginal oral and signed languages, an increase in communication between communities and migration of people to Cairns, the Far North Queensland Indigenous Sign Language has developed, based on mainland and Torres Strait Islander sign languages such as Umpila Sign Language.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The **Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies** (**AIATSIS**), established as the **Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies** (**AIAS**) in 1964, is an independent Australian Government statutory authority.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] It is a collecting, publishing, and research institute and is considered to be Australia's premier resource for information about the cultures and societies of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The institute is a leader in ethical research and the handling of culturally sensitive material.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The collection at AIATSIS has been built through over 50 years of research and engagement with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities and is now a source of language and culture revitalisation, native title research, and Indigenous family and community history.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] AIATSIS is located on Acton Peninsula in Canberra, Australian Capital Territory.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In the late 1950s, there was an increasing focus on the global need for anthropological research into 'disappearing cultures'.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] This trend was also emerging in Australia in the work of researchers of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, leading to a proposal by W.C.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Wentworth MP for the conception of an Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies (AIAS) in 1959.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The proposal was made as a submission to Cabinet, and argued for a more comprehensive approach by the Australian Government to the recording of Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples and cultures.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In 1960, a Cabinet sub-committee assessed the proposal and formed a working party at the Australian National University (ANU) to consider the viability of the proposal.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] One of their first actions was to appoint W.E.H.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Stanner to organise a conference on the state of Aboriginal Studies in Australia, to be held in 1961 at the ANU.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Academics and anthropologists in the field of Aboriginal Studies attended the conference, and contributed research papers published in a conference report in 1963.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] No Aboriginal people were present at the conference.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Prime Minister at the time, Robert Menzies, appointed an Interim Council in 1961.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The role of the Interim Council was to plan for a national Aboriginal research organisation and establish how this organisation would interact with existing research and scientific bodies.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Interim Council was also tasked with immediately developing a programme that would identify and address urgent research needs.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Interim Council consisted of 16 members and was chaired by Deputy Vice-Chancellor of the ANU, Professor A.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Trendall, officially recognised as the first chair of the institute now known as AIATSIS.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] In August 1962, a draft constitution for the institute was submitted to the Menzies government, and rejected.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] The Interim Council completed a revised constitution in July 1963.
[src:adam-kendon/australian-institute-of-aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-studies-p01] Amendments to the document included the change from the title 'director' to 'principal' of the institute.
